FROM (VALUES
  ('cross-crawl-dead-bug', 'Neural drills work best when the cue is clear, the dose is small, and the athlete has enough recovery to coordinate cleaner output. This drill links sensory input, posture, timing, and motor action so the athlete practices higher-quality movement rather than simply accumulating fatigue.', 'Belongs in Prepare & Access / Activate because it raises neural organization and movement confidence without meaningful fatigue.', 'Use in the first 5-12 minutes after a light temperature raise. Keep the dose low so readiness improves without creating fatigue.', 'Do not turn this into conditioning, a long fatigue circuit, or a random agility game. The value is a crisp neural signal, an accurate movement answer, and a clean reset. If the athlete gets slower, louder, dizzy, or less coordinated, the set is done.', 'Scale by reducing speed, distance, amplitude, stance challenge, cue choices, or impact first. Progress by adding intent, slightly shorter reaction windows, greater precision, or more sport-specific angles only after the base version is clean.'),
